            </msubsup>
            <mo>=</mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
          <mo>}</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mo>.</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle S^{3}=\left\{(x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})\in \mathbb {R} ^{4}:x_{0}^{2}+x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}=1\right\}.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/efdefd94a7565635aecce116f39bc17bd24ebcca" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -1.005ex; width:53.693ex; height:3.343ex;" alt="S^{3}=\left\{(x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},x_{3})\in {\mathbb  {R}}^{4}:x_{0}^{2}+x_{1}^{2}+x_{2}^{2}+x_{3}^{2}=1\right\}."/></span></dd></dl>
<p>It is often convenient to regard <span class="texhtml"><b>R</b><sup>4</sup></span> as the space with 2 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_numbers" class="mw-redirect" title="Complex numbers">complex dimensions</a> (<span class="texhtml"><b>C</b><sup>2</sup></span>) or the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quaternion" title="Quaternion">quaternions</a> (<span class="texhtml"><b>H</b></span>). The unit 3-sphere is then given by
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle S^{3}=\left\{(z_{1},z_{2})\in \mathbb {C} ^{2}:|z_{1}|^{2}+|z_{2}|^{2}=1\right\}}">
